es © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Bright’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Molyneux was born in 1080, in Sefton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir John de Molyneux, was 30 and her mother, Mrs. John de Molyneux, was 28. She married Sir John Bradshaigh de Sayer in 1099, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1130, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1080–1130":"1080–1130","1068–1113":"1068–1113","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1050–1103":"1050–1103","1052–Female":"1052–Surnud","1080":"1080","ABT 1099":"umbes 1099","1103":"1103","1113":"1113","1068":"1068","1099":"1099","1130":"1130","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","1160":"1160","after 1113":"pärast 1113","Bradshaw, Lancashire, England":"Bradshaw, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sefton, West Derby, Lancashire, England":"Sefton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1080–1130":"1080–1130","1068–1113":"1068–1113","1099–1160":"1099–1160","1050–1103":"1050–1103","1052–Female